rison media, use the user’s preferred `Before` / `Now` or `current` wording, keep labels semantically light, and make captions obviously smaller/closer to the media.\n- Treat blog takedown requests as real content-removal work in the website repo, not as rewrite/discussion tasks.\n- For helper PR-comment workflows, avoid rerunning on every PR update if the user wants “only on open”.\n- For social copy, default to multiple punchy options rather than one polished draft when the user is still searching for the hook.\n- For social copy that is supposed to sound like Marvin, use repo voice evidence first (`api/src/lib/dispatch.ts`, existing Dispatch posts), not generic snark.\n- For Entire research promos, center the main post on Entire’s checkpoint data / product story first; use supporting tools like `pgr` in a reply if needed.\n- For first-launch product announcements, prefer a Linear/Superset-style launch page over repo `CHANGELOG.md` voice; avoid section labels like `Improvements` unless the product already exists publicly.\n- When the user says `find the right link`, verify the canonical public docs/tutorial URL before finalizing launch or marketing copy.\n- For executive-facing feedback dashboards, strip abstract labels, lead with charts, and include a concrete action-plan section.\n- For feedback/insights projects, keep fulfillment/contact data separate from the public artifact by default.\n- For screen recordings or demo prep, default to PATH-swapped binaries named `entire`, a cleaner prompt like `blackgirlbytes`, and short captions/voiceover notes instead of raw temporary binary paths.\n- For outward-facing support replies, keep them concise, accurate, and focused on `why` and the specific resources accessed, not a long permission lecture.\n\n## General Tips\n\n- Memory repo environment: macOS-style filesystem, `zsh`, memory artifacts under `/Users/rizel/.codex/memories/`.\n- In `/Users/rizel/Documents/work/cli` and `/Users/rizel/Documents/work/gitsync`, plain 