{"timestamp":"2026-05-05T16:22:24.188Z","type":"event_msg","payload":{"type":"agent_message","message":"Yeah, I agree. It is not terrible, but it reads more like internal release notes for the skills than a strong public README.\n\nBiggest improvements:\n\n1. **Lead with the user problem**\n   Right now it says “Cross-agent skills and commands powered by Entire,” then immediately lists skills. It should explain the point in plain language:\n   “These skills help agents use Entire history to search previous work, explain why code exists, hand sessions between agents, and turn repeated workflows into reusable skills.”\n\n2. **Move installation higher, but make it decisive**\n   The README currently has a big compatibility section, but no clear “most people should do this” path. It should have one primary install command first, then agent-specific installs as secondary.\n\n3. **Replace “Current behavior” with clearer use cases**\n   “Current behavior” sounds temporary and implementation-heavy. Better sections would be:\n   - “Use this when…”\n   - “What it does”\n   - “Example prompts”\n\n4. **Group the skills by job, not alphabet/inventory**\n   The skills are really four product surfaces:\n   - Find past work: `search`\n   - Explain code provenance: `explain`, `what-happened`\n   - Move work across agents: `session-handoff`\n   - Create reusable workflows: `session-to-skill`\n\n5. **Clarify Entire dependency**\n   The README should say early that these skills are most useful when the repo has Entire checkpoint/session history. Right now that only becomes obvious after reading the skill details.\n\n6. **Add a “Which skill should I use?” table**\n   This repo is perfect for a simple decision table:\n\n   | What you want | Use |\n   | --- | --- |\n   | Find previous work | `search` |\n   | Explain why a function/file exists | `explain` |\n   | Explain a confusing code block | `what-happened` |\n   | Continue another agent’s work | `session-handoff` |\n   | Turn repeated work into a reusable skill | `session-to-skill` |\n\n7. **Push checkpoint resolution lower**\n   “Checkpoint Resolution” is useful, but it is advanced. It should come after Quick Start or maybe under “How it works.”\n\n8. **Fix naming polish**\n   The README has `# Skills` then `## Skills`, which feels unfinished. Also `what-happened` is listed as lowercase in README but the skill front matter name is `What Happened`; worth normalizing the public presentation.\n\nThe shape I’d recommend:\n\n```md\n# Entire Skills\n\nAgent skills for using Entire history: search prior work, explain code provenance,\nhandoff sessions, and turn repeated workflows into reusable skills.\n\n## Install\n\nprimary command\n\n## Quick Start\n\nexample prompts grouped by task\n\n## Which Skill Should I Use?\n\ntable\n\n## Included Skills\n\nshort, user-facing descriptions\n\n## Agent-Specific Installation\n\ndetails accordions\n\n## Requirements\n\nEntire CLI / checkpoint history notes\n\n## How Checkpoints Are Resolved\n\nadvanced details\n```\n\nThe main thing: make it feel like “here’s what this lets your agent do” instead of “here are five markdown files and their current behavior.”","phase":"final_answer","memory_citation":null}}
